This trend began shortly after Jeremy became the leader of the couple, and my colleagues, with whom I thought we had a similar political attitude, have been increasingly demanding that I turn my back on my individual opinions and take a stand on things that I would otherwise never agree with, be it national security issues or the single European market.
After all my public speeches – no matter what I actually said – they start to slander me on social media, demand my resignation, criticize the center-right policy, and tell me that I shouldn’t even be a member of the Labour Party.
This isn't just happening to me.
In fact, I know that I am more fortunate than many of my colleagues, because the comments addressed to me are usually limited to politics.
I admire the professionalism and determination of my colleagues in politics who are forced to face sexist and racist attacks on a daily basis and yet do not run away.
The most disappointing aspect of today’s politics is that attacks at this level have become the norm.
Jeremy Corbyn spoke last week about the Labour Party’s need to promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality, however, is that we have given up diversity, and with every “distrust” motion and every change in the electoral rules, the tolerance of the party is narrowing.
Over the years, many have advised me to hold back, not to be so outspoken, and then “everything will be fine.”
That’s not why I went into politics.
Thirty-two years ago, I joined the Labour Party as a student because I was outraged that the Thatcher government had neglected schools so much that our classroom almost collapsed, and then I fought for better public care for the most deprived, both as a local councilor and as a government minister.
I never hid my political views, nor did I do otherwise in the last election.
In Nottingham East, it was clear to everyone what my political positions were and on which issues I disagreed with the current leadership.
To those who supported the motion on Friday, I would like to say that in this situation, when the country is moving towards a Brexit that will harm not only families, but also companies and public services, I do not understand why so much time and energy has to be devoted to questioning my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
My most important message, however, is not to the members of the Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether they are members of the Labour Party or not: I am proud to serve you, and I promise that no threat of dismissal or political purpose will deter me from acting in my own judgment and in the interests of all.
Chris Leslie, Representative of Nottingham East
