"The sea is ours": coastal-free Bolivia hopes the court will reopen its path to the Pacific Ocean
Marines are patrolling a sailed naval headquarters in La Paz.
There are ocean-blue flags on public buildings.
Naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon proclaim the motto: “We have a right to the sea.
It's our duty to recover."
In a coastless Bolivia, the memories of a lost coast, taken by Chile in a bloody 19th-century conflict for resources, are still alive, and there is a strong desire to revive the waves of the Pacific.
These hopes are perhaps the ones that have gained momentum in decades, as Bolivia is awaiting the judgment of the International Court of Justice on 1 October, which concludes five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the ball, which is infusing people with a spirit of belonging and peace, who are looking forward to the outcome in a positive mood,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians are watching the decision of the International Court of Justice on screens, hoping that the Hague Court will stand for Bolivia and that Chile will be forced to sit at the negotiating table after decades of rhapsodical attitudes to give Bolivia independent access to the sea.
Bolivia’s charismatic, indigenous president Evo Morales, who faces a controversial fight to be re-elected next year, has a lot to lose with Monday’s verdict.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he said at the end of August.
However, some analysts believe that the court will probably not rule in favour of Bolivia, and it would not change the situation much if it were to do so in favour of Bolivia.
The UN body based in the Netherlands has no authority to judge Chilean territories, and it has also stated in advance that it will not affect the outcome of any possible negotiations.
The fact that the ruling of the International Court of Justice was delivered just six months after the closing remarks indicates that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
In addition, the past four years have not only not helped Bolivia's case, but have even brought it back.
“The issue of the sea exit has been diverted by the current Bolivian government for its own purposes,” Zárate said.
Because of Morales's hostile rhetoric, the Chileans' remaining goodwill has disappeared.
Bolivia and Chile will certainly continue to negotiate at some point, but after what has happened, it will be extremely difficult to initiate a dialogue.
The two countries have not delegated ambassadors to each other since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Veltze, a representative of Bolivia in The Hague, disagrees with the statement that the court decision was unusually quick.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an exceptional opportunity to open a new chapter in its relationship with Chile” and “a chance for both of them to come out well of the end of 139 years of strife,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, had used the naval debate to turn it into a political advantage.
