John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland have traditionally provided excellent education. Looking at the recent outstanding exam results, this situation has not changed by 2018, which is further strengthened by individual and group successes in sports, arts, music and other community initiatives.
In Scotland, more than 30,000 students are already studying in such institutions, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), which strive to provide the best possible service to students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare students for further education, higher education, their chosen careers and their positions as citizens of the world.
In an education sector where it is possible to design and implement customized school curricula, we see that modern languages continue to prove to be popular and sought after subjects.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to someone in a language they understand, they come to their heads.
But if you speak in his own language, it will reach his heart.”
This is an important reminder, because we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s exam results show that students from independent schools across the country have achieved the best results from foreign languages.
Sixty-eight per cent of all students studying a foreign language achieved a higher grade A (more than 85 per cent).
Based on data collected from 74 SCIS member schools, 72 percent of students received a higher grade in Mandarin, while 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students and 63 percent of Spanish students achieved a grade in Mandarin.
These findings also support the fact that independent schools in Scotland see foreign languages as essential knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, languages have become as important as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics in independent and non-independent schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Committee on Employment and Vocational Training found that 17% of employers believe that filling vacancies is difficult because of a lack of language skills.
This shows that language skills are becoming increasingly necessary for young people to have a successful career.
As more and more workplaces require knowledge of foreign languages, language skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have learned a foreign language, you will gain a lifelong lasting knowledge from which you will gain a clear advantage.
The ability to communicate directly with other nationalities automatically gives a competitive advantage to a multilingual candidate.
According to a YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents did not speak a foreign language well enough to communicate with others, and French was the only language spoken by more than 10 percent (15%) of respondents.
This is why it is important to focus on the language education of children.
Speaking several languages, especially those of developing countries, can be a tool in the hands of children to help them apply for important jobs as adults.
Every school in Scotland will have different languages.
Many schools will focus on classical modern languages, while more will teach languages such as Mandarin or Japanese that are expected to be of major importance to the UK by 2020.
Whatever your child’s area of interest, you will be able to learn more than one language at independent schools and will be trained by educators who are experts in their field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment for children that equips and equips them with the skills they will need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It’s not hard to notice that in today’s global business environment, languages continue to be vital to a country’s future, and education should reflect that.
In fact, knowledge of modern languages should be treated as an “international communication skill”.
Independent schools offer young people in Scotland the opportunity of choice, diverse and high-quality education.
Il faut bien le faire – this is how it should be.
John Edward, President of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
