There is no way North Korea will resign unilaterally if it doesn’t trust its negotiating partner.
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that maintaining sanctions has only increased mistrust of the United States, and there is no way the country will unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Jongho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant and generous steps” last year, including halting nuclear and missile testing, closure of nuclear testing sites, and pledging not to expand its nuclear arsenal and the scope of nuclear technology.
“Unfortunately, we don’t see similar responses from the Americans,” he said.
“Without trust in America, we feel that the security of our nation is not guaranteed, and there is no way in these circumstances that we will be unilaterally and first to resign.”
While Ri reaffirmed North Korea’s disappointment at Washington’s resistance to the idea of “phased” nuclear disarmament, which would be expected to reward North Korea for the steps taken so far, his statement seemed meaningful because he did not clearly reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done so far.
Ri cited a joint statement made by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a US president in power and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, during which Kim promised to work on “the nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump guaranteed North Korea’s integrity.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States is of the opinion that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has not given in to tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“America is insisting that we start with nuclear disarmament, and it is increasing the pressure with sanctions to force its will on us, and it is protesting that the end of the war can be declared,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is the dream of those who don’t know us.
The problem is that non-remitting sanctions will only increase our suspicion.”
Ri did not mention that a second summit between Kim and Trump was planned, but the U.S. president spoke specifically at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, he stressed that three meetings had taken place between Kim and South Korean President Mun Jein in the past five months, adding: “If the country involved in the nuclear disarmament were South Korea and not the United States of America, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a stalemate.”
However, the tone of Ri’s speech was dramatically different from last year’s when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting the North American continent with North Korean missiles was unavoidable after Trump, the “evil president,” called Kim “a rocket man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who threatened North Korea with “complete destruction” last year, overwhelmed Kim with praise for his courage to take steps towards disarmament, but also noted that there was still much work to be done and sanctions would remain until North Korea implemented nuclear disarmament.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no time limit, meaning “if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council could reward Pyongyang for the actions taken so far.
In contrast, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said at the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The Security Council’s sanctions must be adhered to scrupulously until we have achieved an actual, final, demonstrable nuclear disarmament.”
The Security Council has unanimously maintained sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in order to reduce funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Riv during the UN General Assembly recess and said he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has been to North Korea three times this year, but his last trip didn’t go very well.
After leaving Pyongyang in July, he announced that progress had been made, but North Korea accused him of making “gangster-like demands” hours later.
At a meeting with Mun this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile base and a nuclear facility if the U.S. took “appropriate action.”
According to Mun, the “suitable steps” mentioned by Kim would be the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and the steps that could lead to the normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students are trained to rest well.
Harvard University’s new subject this year has encouraged students to sleep more, fighting against the increasingly macho culture of caffeinated all-night learning.
One academic concluded that students at the number one university in the world are often completely lost when it comes to how they should care for themselves.
The course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the U.S., was designed by Professor Charles Czeisler, who teaches sleep medicine at Harvard College of Medicine and is practicing as a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital.
He was inspired to develop the course by giving a lecture earlier on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came up to me and asked, ‘Why am I just facing this as a senior?’
He said that no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told the Telegraph.
The course, launched for the first time this year, will show students how good sleep habits have a fundamental impact on their academic and athletic performance, in addition to having a positive impact on their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard College of Medicine and director of the university’s health service, said the university decided to start the course because students were found extremely sleepy during the week.
The one-hour course also includes a series of interactive exercises.
In one, for example, they show a picture of a dorm room where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books to get acquainted with the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by insomnia, and why bedtime routine is important.
In another part, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the university’s area with interactive icons will be presented to encourage participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that we are not going to change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe that they have a right to this knowledge – just as they have a right to be aware of the health effects of smoking,” said Professor Czeisler.
The culture continues to flourish in which it is an accomplishment to learn one night at a time, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students lead to the growing problem of sleeplessness.
Adequate and high-quality sleep is a student’s “secret weapon” in combating stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even protects against obesity, as sleep deprivation forces the brain into a starving mode and causes a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So helped Professor Czeisler design the course, a 19-year-old California student studying chemistry and biophysics, and last year he took a course at Harvard as a first-time professor.
He said that those who heard him there had opened his eyes and encouraged him to advocate a university-level training.
He hopes that as a next step, postgraduate students will be able to participate in a similar training program before they enter the competitive sector.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set a warning to go to bed, wake up to wake up, and get acquainted with the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electrical screens and LED light sources, which can easily drive them out of the daily rhythm and make it difficult to fall asleep.
