A vaccine given as part of a treatment trains the immune system to recognise abnormal cells.
Part of the method is to extract immune cells from the patient and then modify them in a laboratory.
This allows them to "see" the protein that accompanies many types of cancer. The treated immune cells are injected back into the patient.
An experimental vaccine has produced promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize abnormal cells could say goodbye to ovarian cancer for more than 18 months.
The method involves obtaining immune cells from the patient; modifying them in the laboratory to “see” a protein called HER2, which is a common accompaniment to several types of cancer; and then transplanting the cells.
Jay Berzofsky, a professor at the American National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our findings suggest we have a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 “stimulates the growth of several types of cancers, including breast, ovarian, lung and rectal cancers,” Berzofsky explained.
A similar method, based on stimulating immune cells and “teaching” them how to attack cancer cells, has already been successfully used in the treatment of one type of leukemia.
