What is the Global Citizen Festival and have you managed to mitigate poverty?
On Saturday, the annual New York City Music Festival, the Global Citizen Festival, begins. World stars perform at the festival to stand up for a truly noble goal: the global eradication of poverty.
The Global Citizen Festival will be held for the seventh time, with tens of thousands expected to fill the Great Lawn of Central Park, where participants will not only enjoy Janet Jackson, Cardi B or Shawn Mendes’ performance, but also raise awareness of the true purpose of the event: to eradicate extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival was first organised in 2012 as part of the Global Poverty Project, which is run by an international advocacy group that aims to eradicate poverty by engaging more and more people in the active fight against poverty.
Free tickets to the concert are available to those (unless they are willing to pay for a VIP ticket) who undertake certain tasks or “activities” such as volunteering, sending an email to a senior politician, a phone call, or any other meaningful activity to raise awareness of the goal of the project: the eradication of poverty.
But how successful has the Global Citizen really been in achieving its goals over the past 12 years?
Is it really an effective way to reward people with concert tickets to convince others of the importance of action, or is it just another form of so-called “clicktivism” where people feel they have contributed substantially to a case by signing an online petition or writing a tweet?
Since 2011, according to Global Citizen data, more than 19 million “actions” have been carried out by project sponsors, serving a variety of different purposes.
According to the organization, these actions have helped global leaders allocate <0x24>37 billion to anti-poverty policies and commitments that could impact the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group claimed that 390 commitments and announcements came from their actions, of which <0x24>10 billion had already been paid out or raised through fundraising.
The group estimates that the money collected directly affected the lives of nearly 649 million people.
The main commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based partnership between investors and contractors to “help children reach their full potential.” The organization pledged Rwanda <0x24>35 million to help eradicate hunger after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from “global citizens.”
“With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and global citizens like you, we can banish social injustice and malnutrition to the footnotes of history books,” said Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of Power of Nutrition to the crowd at a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also claims that after asking the UK for more than 5,000 actions to improve the nutrition of mothers and their children, the government allocated funds to the Power of Nutrition project, which will improve the nutrition of 5 million women and children.
One of the most frequently asked questions on the Global Citizen website is: “Why do you think extreme poverty can be eradicated?”
The Global Citizen replies: “It will be a long and difficult journey, sometimes stalled and sometimes failed.
But like previous civil rights and anti-segregation movements, we will achieve our goal because together we are stronger.”
Among others, Janet Jackson, Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe will perform at this year’s New York event, with Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman as presenters.
