“If you consider the structure and facilities of the club, it is undoubtedly its place in the first league,” he said.
“It will not be easy to get back, but it is more than likely that I will only consider my activities here a success if I can bring the club back.”
Ross’ managerial career began just three years ago, after working as a deputy coach for Dumbarton for a while, as well as spending 15 months on the Hearts coaching team.
He then helped Aolla recover after the team dropped back into the third division, and with St. Mirren, who was on the verge of elimination, he won the championship the following season.
Ross says he feels more confident now than he has ever felt in his career as a player, whether with Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St. Mirren or Hamilton Academic.
"It was a decisive moment," he said, recalling his time as a coach for Alloa.
“I definitely thought management was better for me than being a player.
That sounds strange, because I did it well, I lived it quite well, I even had some really memorable moments.
The lives of the players are sometimes very difficult.
We have a lot to go through every blessed week.
Of course, I still have to deal with the stress and pressure of work, but the management tasks lie with me.
I’ve always been interested in managing, and now that I’ve tasted it, I feel the best in my skin all my adult life.”
