Earthquakes and tsunami in Indonesia
At least 384 people were killed in a massive earthquake on Friday, followed by a tsunami in the Indonesian city of Palu.
The area’s communications network was also damaged, so no news has yet been received from Donggala Governorate, north of Palu, where the earthquake of magnitude 7.5 was the centre.
More than 16,000 people had to be evacuated in Palu.
Some important facts about Palu and Donggala on the island of Celebes:
The capital of Palu Central Celebes, on the west coast of the island of Celebes, was built at the end of a narrow bay with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when it was struck by an earthquake and tsunami.
Donggala Governorate is more than 300 km long on the northwest coast of Celebes Island.
The population of the Governorate, a smaller administrative region than the province, was approximately 299,200 in 2017.
Central Celebes is mainly characterised by fishing and farming, especially in the coastal areas of Donggala.
Nickel mining is an important sector of the economy, but it is mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the other side of Celebes.
According to the Indonesian Disaster Response Agency, Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times over the past 100 years.
A tsunami in 1938 killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
In 1996, a tsunami hit Western Donggala, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the geologically active Pacific Fire Ring area, so earthquakes are common.
Some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: On December 26, a massive sea quake began on the west coast of the Aceh province of North Sumatra, triggering a tsunami that hit 14 countries, killing a total of 226,000 people along the Indian Ocean coastline, killing more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra between the end of March and the beginning of April.
On the island of Nias, near Sumatra, hundreds of people died.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake hit the southern part of Java, Indonesia's largest island, and a tsunami in its wake killed nearly 700 people on the southern coast.
2009: 7.6 earthquake near Padang, the capital of Western Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people lost their lives.
2010: A magnitude 7.5 earthquake hit an island in the Mentawa archipelago near Sumatra, causing a 10-metre tsunami that devastated dozens of villages and claimed about 300 lives.
2016: A near-surface quake hit the governorship of Aceh Pidie Jaya. The panic and devastation that arose in its wake evoked the memories of the terrible tsunami of 2004 in many people.
The tsunami did not occur this time, but more than 100 residents were killed under the collapsed buildings.
2018: Lombok is an Indonesian island popular with tourists; a powerful quake here claimed 500 lives, especially in the northern part of the island.
Thousands of buildings were destroyed, and thousands of tourists were trapped on the island for a while.
